Trimmed mean of M values (TMM normalization): average after removing the top and bottom X% (default in edge R = trim M values/log2 FC by 30% & trim A values/mean expression by 5%)

Estimate dispersion

# calculate overall dispersion
DGE <- estimateGLMCommonDisp(DGE, design, verbose = TRUE) 
## Disp = 0.03062 , BCV = 0.175
# calculate dispersion trend based on gene abundance
DGE <- estimateGLMTrendedDisp(DGE, design) 

# calculate separate dispersion for each gene
DGE <- estimateGLMTagwiseDisp(DGE, design)
  • Based on the design, estimateGLMCommonDisp can calculate within-group and between-group variability.
  • The BCV captures all sources of inter-library variation between replicates, including contributions from technical causes such as library preparation, as well as true biological variation between samples.
  • Here, the common dispersion estimate is 0.03318, the square root of which is 0.1822 (=BCV).
  • Interpretation: on average, the true abundance for each gene can vary up or down by 18 % between replicates.
  • Knowing how well replicate samples correlate helps to distinguish a true treatment effect from random noise.
  • The tag-wise dispersion model allows for a different value for the dispersion to be used for each gene (recommended method).

GLM likelihood ratio test for identifying DE genes

The GLM likelihood ratio test is based on the idea of fitting negative binomial GLMs with the Cox-Reid dispersion estimates. This takes all known sources of variation into account. Therefore, the GLM likelihood ratio test is recommended for experiments with multiple factors.

Fit a gene-wise negative binomial generalized linear model

fit <- glmFit(DGE, design)
colnames(fit$coefficients)
## [1] "(Intercept)" "Sinfo$Code1" "Sinfo$Code2"

Conduct likelihood ratio test to identify DE genes of PA treatment

lrt1 <- glmLRT(fit, coef = "Sinfo$Code1") #specify the comparison of interest
topTags(lrt1)
